[1]
Date: Thu 13 Dec 2007
From: Eugene Pipano <pipano@agri.huji.ac.il>


Re: Babesiosis, tigers - India (Bhopal): suspected, request for information
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
[Upon ProMED-mail's request, the following background information on
babesiosis in felines has been kindly forwarded by Prof Eugene
Pipano, Koret School of Veterinary Medicine, Rehovot, Israel -- for
which we are grateful. - Mod.AS]

Three species of _Babesia_ are known in wild felids: _Babesia felis_,
_B. leo_, and _B. herpailuri_ (_B. pantherae_ ?). Unidentified
_Babesia_ parasites have been reported from various parts of the
world. _Babesia_ parasites are undergoing re-classification on the
basis of molecular analysis.

It is assumed that, similar to the transmission of _Babesia_
parasites in other animal species, _Babesia_ parasites in felids are
transmitted by ticks. However, to date no ticks have been
identified as vectors of feline babesiosis.

The following drugs are recommended in felids suffering from babesiosis
1. Primaquine sulfate (also used for treatment of human malaria) at
doses of about 0.5 mg/kg.
2. Clindamycin: the usual dose in cats is 5-10 mg/pound by mouth, once a day.
3. Some authors recommend treatment with oxytetracycline (OTC) [see
reference re bovines].
4. Various other drugs, mainly antimalarials, have been used to treat
felids with babesiosis.

Another question is whether the parasites seen in this specific tiger
were indeed _Babesia_ sp.. Domestic cats and wild felids
are susceptible to a parasite belonging to the genus _Theileria_,
_Cytauxzoon felis_, and the erythrocytic stages of this parasite are
rather similar to _Babesia_ parasites in microscope slides.

Reference:
Pipano E, Krigel Y, Markovics A, Rubinstein E & Frank M. (1985):
Mitigation of the response of Friesian calves to live _Babesia bovis_
vaccine by treatment with long acting oxytetracycline. Vet Rec.
117(16): 413-4.

--
E. Pipano, DVM, PhD
Koret School of Veterinary Medicine
Hebrew University
Rehovot campus
<pipano@agri.huji.ac.il>

