[3]
Date: Thu 13 Dec 2007
From: Jason Maguire <Jason.Maguire@med.navy.mil>


The tigers may well have babesiosis but the presence of severe
gastritis and clinical description sound like possible _Galoncus
perniciosus_ (hookworm) infection. There was a similar die off of
tigers with diarrhea and wasting at the Ragunan Zoo outside Jakarta
[Indonesia] in 2001 that was ultimately attributed to this parasite.

--
Jason D Maguire, MD, MPH
Head, Infectious Diseases Division
Travelers' Health Clinic
Naval Medical Center Portsmouth
Portsmouth, Virginia 23708
USA
<Jason.Maguire@med.navy.mil>

[The hookworm _Galoncus perniciosus _ has been found also to infect
lions in Northern Rhodesia; see Le Roux, PL 1958. Trans. R. Soc.
Trop. Med. Hyg. 52: 14 and a leopard in India, see Death of a wild
Indian leopard, Panthera pardus Fusca (Meyer) due to parasitism with
lung fluke Paragonimus westermanii (Kerbert, 1878) and the hookworm
Galoncus perniciosus (Linstow, 1885). J. Vet. Anim. Sci., 24 (1): 44-46.
For more background on the current case, see Mod.PC's commentary in
ProMED-mail post 20071211.3990. - Mod.AS/JW]
